b'' b':can anyone out there tell me the difference between a "persistent" disease' b':and a "chronic" one? for example, persistent hepatitis vs chronic' b':hepatitis.' b':' b":i don't think there is a general distinction. rather, there are" b':two classes of chronic hepatitis: chronic active hepatitis and chronic' b":persistent hepatitis. i can't think of any other disease where the" b':term persistent is used with or in preference to chronic.' b':' b':much as these two terms "chronic active" and "chronic persistent"' b':sound fuzzy, the actual distinction between the two conditions' b':is often fairly fuzzy as well.' b'' b'i beg to differ. chronic *active* hepatitis implies that the disease' b'remains active, and generally leads to liver failure. at the very' b'minimum, the patient has persistently elevated liver enzymes (what some' b'call "transaminitis"). chronic *persistant* hepatitis simply means that' b'the patient has hbsag in his/her blood and can transmit the infection, but' b"shows no evidence of progressive disease. if i had to choose, i'd much" b'rather have the persistant type.' b'' b'--' b'=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-|-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=' b'= kenneth gilbert university of pittsburgh b'= general internal medicine "...dammit, not a programmer!" b'=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-|-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=' 